During Week 2, I worked on several medium-level challenges that focused mainly on digital forensics, data encoding, and file analysis in picoCTF. The challenges included DISKO 3, DISKO 2, Event-Viewing, Bitlocker-2, Bitlocker-1, Blast from the Past, Mob Psycho, Endianness-v2, Dear Diary, PcapPoisoning, MSB, hideme, FindAndOpen, and Torrent Analyze. These tasks required deeper investigation of files, hidden data, and encoded information compared to the earlier beginner challenges.
Throughout the week, I learned how to analyze different types of digital artifacts such as disk images, encrypted files, packet captures, and hidden image data. Many challenges required the use of command-line tools in the picoCTF webshell such as wget, strings, cat, ls, and other forensic utilities. I also used external analysis tools like Wireshark for examining packet capture files and CyberChef for decoding encoded data such as Base64 and other formats.
One of the key skills I practiced was analyzing hidden information within files. Some challenges involved steganography techniques such as MSB and LSB extraction, where data is hidden within the pixel values of images. Other tasks required checking metadata, investigating unusual file headers, or extracting hidden files from archives. I also encountered challenges that required analyzing network traffic and reconstructing information from packet data, which improved my understanding of how network forensic investigations work.
Another important lesson this week was learning how data can be encoded or represented in different formats, such as hexadecimal values, byte ordering (endianness), or encoded text. Understanding these representations helped me decode hidden messages and reconstruct flags from fragmented information.
The biggest challenge during this week was encountering unfamiliar tools and techniques, especially when dealing with encryption, packet captures, and steganography. However, I was able to overcome these difficulties by researching the commands, reviewing documentation, and practicing the steps repeatedly. This process helped me gradually become more comfortable with command-line tools and forensic analysis methods.
Overall, Week 2 significantly improved my problem-solving skills, familiarity with digital forensic tools, and understanding of how attackers or analysts hide and recover information from digital evidence. These challenges also reinforced the importance of carefully examining files, paying attention to hints, and testing multiple approaches when analyzing suspicious data.
For the next week, I plan to continue practicing forensic commands and tools so I can analyze files more efficiently and rely less on tutorials when solving more advanced cybersecurity challenges.
